# 🧠 Strategy Design Pattern – Notes

## 🔹 What is Strategy Pattern?

* A **behavioral design pattern**
* Used when **one task can be done in multiple ways**
* You **encapsulate each way (strategy)** into separate classes
* At runtime, you can **choose which strategy to use**

👉 Simple line:

> **“Same kaam, different tareeke → Strategy Pattern”**

---

## 🔹 Real-world Example (Notification System)

You want to send notifications via:

* Email
* SMS
* WhatsApp
* Push Notification

👉 All do **same task = send notification**
👉 But **implementation different**

---

## ❌ Without Strategy Pattern (Bad Design)

```java
if(type == EMAIL) { ... }
else if(type == SMS) { ... }
else if(type == PUSH) { ... }
```

### 🚨 Problems:

1. ❌ Violates **Open-Closed Principle (OCP)**

   * New channel → modify existing code

2. ❌ Violates **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**

   * One class doing:

     * deciding type ❌
     * sending notification ❌

3. ❌ Too many `if-else` (Interview red flag 💀)

👉 Golden rule:

> **“Zyada if-else = design kharab”**

---

## ✅ With Strategy Pattern (Good Design)

### 1. Create Strategy Interface

```java
interface NotificationStrategy {
    void send(String msg);
}
```

---

### 2. Create Concrete Classes

```java
class EmailNotification implements NotificationStrategy {
    public void send(String msg) {
        // email logic
    }
}

class SMSNotification implements NotificationStrategy {
    public void send(String msg) {
        // sms logic
    }
}
```

---

### 3. Context Class (Main Service)

```java
class NotificationService {
    private NotificationStrategy strategy;

    public NotificationService(NotificationStrategy strategy) {
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    public void send(String msg) {
        strategy.send(msg);
    }
}
```

---

### 4. Client Code

```java
NotificationService service =
    new NotificationService(new EmailNotification());

service.send("Hello");
```

---

## 🔥 Key Concepts

### ✔ Interface = Strategy

* Groups all similar behaviors

### ✔ Concrete Classes = Different Strategies

* Each class = one implementation

### ✔ Runtime Behavior Change

* You can switch strategy dynamically

---

## 🎯 Advantages

✅ No if-else
✅ Follows OCP (extend without modifying)
✅ Follows SRP
✅ Clean & maintainable code
✅ Easy to add new features

---

## ➕ Adding New Feature (WhatsApp)

Just do:

```java
class WhatsAppNotification implements NotificationStrategy {
    public void send(String msg) {
        // whatsapp logic
    }
}
```

👉 No change in existing classes ✔️
👉 Only new class added ✔️

